      "question": "A box contains $90$ discs which are numbered from $1$ to $90$. If one disc is drawn at random from the box, find the probability that it bears: (i) a two-digit number, (ii) a perfect square number.",
      "answer": "The probability of (i) is $\\frac{9}{10}$ and (ii) is $\\frac{1}{10}$.",
      "solution": {
        "steps": [
          "Identify the total number of possible outcomes, which is $90$.",
          "For (i), identify the two-digit numbers from $10$ to $90$. There are $90 - 9 = 81$ such numbers. The probability is $\\frac{81}{90} = \\frac{9}{10}$.",
          "For (ii), identify the perfect squares between $1$ and $90$. These are $1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81$. There are $9$ such numbers. The probability is $\\frac{9}{90} = \\frac{1}{10}$."
        ],
        "derivation": "Total \\ outcomes \\ n(S) = 90 \\\\ (i) \\ Two-digit \\ numbers \\ are \\ \\{10, 11, \\dots, 90\\}, \\ n(E_1) = 90 - 9 = 81 \\\\ P(E_1) = \\frac{81}{90} = \\frac{9}{10} \\\\ (ii) \\ Perfect \\ squares \\ are \\ \\{1^2, 2^2, 3^2, 4^2, 5^2, 6^2, 7^2, 8^2, 9^2\\} = \\{1, 4, 9, 16, 25, 36, 49, 64, 81\\}, \\ n(E_2) = 9 \\\\ P(E_2) = \\frac{9}{90} = \\frac{1}{10}"
      },
